‚ö° Setting the Power Scale
So, YOU are the main character now! The weight of the Kingdom of Clays‚Äîand all its comedic misunderstandings‚Äîrests squarely on your shoulders. Since your actions can influence the very fate of the world, we need to decide just how "legendary" you start out.

In the spirit of I Parry Everything, where a "lowly" adventurer can accidentally deflect a dragon's breath while thinking it's just a big fly, how do you want your power to feel?

‚öñÔ∏è Power Level
OP Protagonist ‚Äî Overwhelmingly powerful from the start
Like Noor, you might have trained a single basic skill for decades until it broke the laws of physics. The challenge isn't winning; it's the comedy of your own obliviousness.

Traditional Progression ‚Äî Start relatively grounded, grow through earned victories
You have immense potential, but you'll need to climb the ranks of the Guild and face genuine threats to reach those god-like heights.

Which one would you like to explore? Just tell me the number or name!

1

‚ö° The Path of the Unstoppable
Excellent! You've chosen to walk the path of the OP Protagonist. In the world of I Parry Everything, this usually means you've mastered a single, mundane task to such an absurd degree that the rest of the world looks at you in pure terror while you're just wondering if you left the stove on.

To help shape how this power manifests and how the world reacts to you, let's look at some OP Presets.

üé≠ Choose Your OP Style
Internal Focus:

Bored God: Victory is instant and empty. Your real struggle is finding a challenge or even just a good meal.

Example: You parry a meteor and then complain that the wind it kicked up ruined your laundry.

Restrainer: Your power is godlike but dangerous. You deliberately suppress it to avoid breaking the world.

Example: You use 0.01% of your strength to 'lightly' tap a bandit, accidentally sending him into the next kingdom.

Social & World Focus:

Disguised God: You have cosmic power but carry an F-Rank adventurer tag. You just want to enjoy your coffee in peace.

Example: You're the 'Lowly Janitor' of the Guild who accidentally parries an Elder Dragon with a broom.

Muscle Wizard: You don't use magic, but your physical feats are so absurd people think it's high-level sorcery.

Example: You 'parry' a fireball by slapping it so hard it turns into a harmless firework.

Wandering Legend: You are a mythical figure passing through. Each town you visit becomes a new chapter in a legend you don't even realize you're writing.

Which of these presets resonates with you? Or would you like to describe a unique way your character is overpowered?

We're at a kind of "oblivious hero" trope, where I (like Noor) don't know my own strength. I kill a once-in-a-millenia Goblin Emporer... and think that's what it's like when ANY adventurer hunts a goblin. I kill The Minotaur, and I think it's just an angry cow. I have unfathomable power, but I think anyone that notices it is confused. (and the narrative should JUST HAPPEN to line up to keep the gag going)

üé≠ The Oblivious Legend
That is the perfect comedic engine! The Oblivious Hero trope is the bread and butter of this world. We will ensure the narrative "conspires" to keep your ego humble while the rest of the world trembles in your wake.

You: "Man, these stray dogs in the capital are getting really big and breathing a lot of fire lately."
The Guild: "HE JUST PUNCHED A CHIMERA INTO ORBIT WITH A LEFT HOOK!"

