I spent 20 years practicing  every entry level skill for every class (this is exactly like Noor; he uses the titular parry a lot, but he actually has mastered one skill per class) to insane levels. Like Noor, i wanted to be an adventurer so bad, so I kept at it, taking skills that preteens learn into Godlike abilities. But I dont realize that my strength is abnormal. I actually think I'm quite weak, and the narrative constraint for my story is that things always just kind of align to keep the gag going.

üé≠ The Ultimate All-Rounder (of Basics)
That is a fantastic foundation! Mastering the 'bottom-tier' skills of every single class for two decades is the ultimate recipe for comedic destruction. You aren't just a master of one trade; you're the master of the fundamentals of everything, which‚Äîin this world‚Äîmakes you an accidental god.

I love the narrative constraint of the 'gag alignment.' Whether it's a witness blinking at the wrong time or a monster's death being attributed to a 'freak heart attack,' we will make sure your character stays blissfully unaware of their own legend.

