Phase 5: Your Story Begins
The sun is high over the trade-hub of Utz, casting long shadows across your small farmstead. You‚Äôve spent the morning "tidying up" the perimeter. A pack of 'Great-Horned Shadow Wolves'‚Äîcreatures that usually require a B-Rank party to cull‚Äîhad the misfortune of being classified as "overgrown stray dogs" in your mind. You shooed them away with a few light taps of your black training sword, accidentally snapping their reinforced ribcages and sending them whimpering back into the dense magical forest.

Now, you‚Äôre standing at the edge of your property, wiping a bit of dust off your boots with a quick Cleanse. The air suddenly ripples with a strange, oppressive heat. From the direction of the mountain pass, a massive, crimson-scaled Wyvern‚Äîa 'Calamity-Class' threat‚Äîscreeches as it dives toward the merchant caravans heading for the Utz gates. To the guards on the wall, it‚Äôs a nightmare. To you, it looks like a very large, very loud pigeon that‚Äôs about to poop on the roof you just fixed.

You reach into your satchel and find a particularly smooth pebble.

The Wyvern is closing in on the caravan, and the guards are screaming in terror. What do you do, Deus?

I recall a time when, around 13--several years into my training--I had run back home and into the house to ask my mom what I should do with "this bird I found outside in the garden". She had told me "Just toss a stone at it and it'll fly away, my little bugbear. It'll scurry right off on it's own." I had promptly gone outside and done as she said, flinging a chunk of lead so hard the friction lit the air on fire behind it. The drag created winds that threatened to rip the Wyven from the sky, and the sonic bomb left is dazed and disoriented. It had flown away, staggering haphazardly across the sky, 

Mom was right.

I smile and wave at the guards as I run up behind them at the town gate. "Morning fellas! Here, let me get take care of this little fella for you." I say, as I gather a softball sized chunk of rock from the ground, throwing it so hard it spins the Wyvern around thrice as though it were caught in a vortex, winding down until it's looking directly at me. It takes only a moment before it recognizes me, and turns to run at escape velocity.

"Morning fellas!"

The cheerful greeting cuts through the panic at the gate like a knife through soft butter. While the guards cower behind their pikes, trembling at the shadow looming overhead, Deus jogs past them with the casual energy of a man heading to the market. He crouches, fingers digging into the hard-packed earth, and wrenches free a jagged rock the size of a grapefruit.

To him, it is a pebble. To the laws of physics, it is a violation waiting to happen.

He shifts his weight. The ground beneath his right boot spiders with hairline fractures‚Äînot from a stomp, but from the silent, terrifying transfer of torque grounding itself into the bedrock. His arm goes back, the motion fluid, practiced, perfected through years of boredom until the mechanics of the throw have transcended muscle and become pure instinct.

Skill: Pebble Shot.

CRACK.

There is no whoosh of air. There is only the deafening thunderclap of the atmosphere collapsing into a vacuum where the stone used to be. The projectile doesn't fly; it teleports, becoming a streak of superheated friction that tears a visible, shimmering scar across the blue sky. A cone of condensed white vapor erupts around the path of the stone, the sonic boom blasting the dust off the city walls.

High above, the Wyvern is mid-dive, a predator assured of its meal. Then, the sky punches it in the face.

The stone strikes the beast's snout with the kinetic impact of a siege cannon. The shockwave ripples backward through the creature's skull, sending a shudder through its entire skeletal structure that is visible from the ground. But the impact is only half the punishment.

The wake of the stone‚Äîthe sheer displacement of air caused by the impossible velocity‚Äîcreates a localized vortex. The atmosphere twists into a horizontal tornado, catching the multi-ton reptile in its grip. The Wyvern is yanked out of its trajectory and spun violently‚Äîonce, twice, thrice‚Äîragdolled by the wind pressure alone until it is facing the wrong way, dizzy and hovering in a stall.

As the vortex dissipates, the beast shakes its head, vision clearing just enough to look down the barrel of the attack. It sees the gate. It sees the small, waving figure.

The Boy.

Primal terror overrides hunger. The Wyvern's pupils dilate to pinpricks. It doesn't turn; it scrambles backward against the air itself, wings beating with frantic, desperate energy. It breaks the sound barrier in retreat, leaving a trail of terrified clouds as it flees the monster disguised as a man.

"Sorry guys, I can't stay, but here's some apples for lunch! I just harvested them last night!" I say, tossing a small satchel of apples up to the guard's post, before continuing my morning run to the adventurer's guild

The morning mist over Utz doesn‚Äôt just part for Deus; it shatters.

He is a blur of motion, a streak of nondescript adventurer‚Äôs garb cutting a vacuum tunnel through the dense air. He doesn't decelerate as he approaches the watchtower‚Äîif anything, his stride lengthens, the rhythmic thud-thud-thud of his boots hitting the cobblestone with the precision of a metronome set to overdrive.

"Sorry guys, I can't stay!"

The voice arrives a split-second after his image registers in the guards' retinas. Deus pivots at the waist‚Äîmomentum completely unchecked‚Äîand his arm snaps forward in a perfect, fluid arc.

Whoosh.

The satchel leaves his hand. It doesn't tumble; it spirals like a rifled shell, cutting a parabolic trajectory so mathematically flawless it seems to mock the wind itself. Time seems to hang suspended‚Äîan impact frame of the brown burlap sack silhouetted against the blinding morning sun.

"But here's some apples for lunch! I just harvested them last night!"

The guard atop the post reacts on pure instinct, his body moving before his brain can process the projectile. His gauntleted hand snaps up.

THWACK.

The impact stings his palm, not from force, but from the sheer density of the delivery. The guard stumbles back a half-step, clutching the prize to his chest. He looks down. The bag is still spinning slightly in his grip. He opens it, and a golden, ethereal aroma wafts out‚Äîapples so pristine, so perfectly preserved without a single bruise despite the velocity, that they seem to glow with an inner vitality.

By the time the guard looks up, mouth agape at the holy bounty in his hands, Deus is already gone‚Äîa dwindling speck on the horizon, leaving only a swirling vortex of dust and the lingering echo of casual benevolence in his wake.